WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.389
Welcome to your Bookmarks Digest for Wednesday, June 17, 2026.

00:00:04.389 --> 00:00:09.273
One story bends almost everything you saved today: on Friday the U.S.

00:00:09.273 --> 00:00:16.068
government forced Anthropic to pull its most powerful models, Fable 5 and Mythos, off the table.

00:00:16.068 --> 00:00:39.143
So we open there — the economics, the politics, and a builder's view — then move to what it's like to actually work with these models, then markets and tech, attention and society, a turn through geopolitics and history, and we close with the long read: a new paper putting a dollar figure on what AI is doing to productivity.

00:00:39.143 --> 00:00:42.399
Every word came from something you bookmarked.

00:00:42.399 --> 00:00:44.664
Use the chapters to jump around.

00:00:44.664 --> 00:00:45.372
Settle in.

00:00:45.372 --> 00:00:52.414
We open where the whole day points: Friday's government order pulling Anthropic's Fable 5 and Mythos.

00:00:52.414 --> 00:00:54.087
A few short takes first.

00:00:54.087 --> 00:00:59.038
Dean Ball, on whether AI deserves protection under the First Amendment.

00:00:59.038 --> 00:01:10.264
segyges Because a ruling that protects AI under the first amendment would be disastrous for the company’s broader regulatory agenda, would be my uninformed guess

00:01:10.264 --> 00:01:15.631
Neil Chilson flags the latest reporting on the Fable and Mythos story.

00:01:15.631 --> 00:01:24.678
New reporting on the Fable/Mythos story links last Friday’s export-control decision to the June 2 AI Cybersecurity EO.

00:01:24.678 --> 00:01:28.742
It also bears out one warning I raised about that EO.

00:01:28.742 --> 00:01:32.959
Here’s a short “I regret to report I was right” thread.

00:01:32.959 --> 00:01:33.112
1/

00:01:33.112 --> 00:01:39.680
The administration's AI czar, David Sacks, pushes back on what he calls a misleading narrative.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:48.806
Some recent articles have created a misleading narrative that I did not take Mythos seriously or tried to downplay the cyber threat.

00:01:48.806 --> 00:01:58.140
This is based on egregious cherry-picking of my comments and (since the real target is the Trump Administration) needs to be corrected.

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:18.398
When Mythos Preview first launched, I pointed out that Anthropic has a history of scare tactics, but then immediately went on to say that “we have no choice but to take this seriously” and that every CISO and IT department should move quickly to harden systems against AI-powered cyberattacks.

00:02:18.398 --> 00:02:33.954
Here’s what I said on the April 10 All-In Podcast (3 days after launch of Mythos Preview):

“Anytime Anthropic is scaring people, you have to ask, is this a tactic, is this part of their chicken little routine, or is it real?

00:02:33.954 --> 00:02:40.729
With cyber, I actually would give them credit in this case and say, this is more on the real side.

00:02:40.729 --> 00:02:48.611
“It just makes sense that as the coding models become more and more capable, they’re more capable of finding bugs.

00:02:48.611 --> 00:02:52.690
That means they’re more capable of finding vulnerabilities.

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:59.811
That means they’re more capable of stringing together multiple vulnerabilities and creating an exploit.

00:02:59.811 --> 00:03:23.526
“I do think that every company, or IT department, or CISO that is managing code bases should take this seriously and use the next few months to detect any dormant bugs or vulnerabilities and roll out patches.”

I posted similar framing on X:

On April 10: “The world has no choice but to take the cyber threat associated with Mythos seriously.

00:03:23.526 --> 00:03:30.232
But it’s hard to ignore that Anthropic has a history of scare tactics.” (With examples attached).

00:03:30.232 --> 00:03:45.512
On April 12: I noted that a growing number of people were wondering if Anthropic was the AI industry’s “boy who cried wolf,” and that the company would face a serious credibility problem if the threats didn’t materialize.

00:03:45.512 --> 00:03:48.485
These are the lines the articles highlight.

00:03:48.485 --> 00:04:00.100
They emphasize the “scare tactics” / “boy who cried wolf” critique while omitting the parts where I said the cyber threat itself was real and required immediate action.

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:10.263
It is entirely possible to question a messenger’s track record while still treating the underlying risk as serious — and that’s exactly what I did.

00:04:10.263 --> 00:04:22.224
By the way, this view isn’t unique to me or even particularly controversial; highly respected tech commentator Ben Thompson recently made a similar critique about Anthropic.

00:04:22.224 --> 00:04:33.632
On April 30 I posted a more technical thread after tests by the AI Security Institute showed that GPT-5.5-Cyber performed similarly to Mythos:

“Mythos is not magic.

00:04:33.632 --> 00:04:35.499
It’s not a doomsday device.

00:04:35.499 --> 00:04:40.961
It’s the first of many models that can automate cyber tasks (just like coding).

00:04:40.961 --> 00:04:45.455
… these models do not create vulnerabilities; they discover them.

00:04:45.455 --> 00:04:47.736
The bugs are already in the code.

00:04:47.736 --> 00:04:52.645
Using AI to discover and patch them will actually harden these systems.

00:04:52.645 --> 00:04:58.867
“The leap from pre-AI cyber to post-AI cyber means that there will be a big upgrade cycle.

00:04:58.867 --> 00:05:03.845
… it’s important that cyber defenders get access before cyber attackers.

00:05:03.845 --> 00:05:16.843
That process is already underway but needs to happen quickly.”

My position remains consistent: We are on a shot clock until Mythos-level capabilities diffuse widely, including to non-U.S.

00:05:16.843 --> 00:05:18.019
/ Chinese models.

00:05:18.019 --> 00:05:22.997
We need defenders to find and patch vulnerabilities before that happens.

00:05:22.997 --> 00:05:27.007
This requires cooperation between government and industry.

00:05:27.007 --> 00:05:35.303
Unfortunately Anthropic’s needlessly confrontational posture toward the Administration has distracted from that mission.

00:05:35.303 --> 00:05:42.424
Policy debates have their time and place, but right now tangible defensive action is what matters most.

00:05:42.424 --> 00:05:45.466
I hope everyone moves forward on that basis.

00:05:45.466 --> 00:05:51.140
A builder's-eye view from Rahul, on how to think about this new class of models.

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:56.104
I've lightly smoothed his thread for listening, but the ideas are his.

00:05:56.104 --> 00:06:00.572
Here's a mental model for the new class of models like Fable 5.

00:06:00.572 --> 00:06:15.110
It's more correct to think of them as English-to-code interpreters: they convert your idea into code, and into "correct" code, regardless of how complex the problem is or how large the resulting change is.

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:22.273
Fable 5 will be the worst member of this new class — which is to say, they only get better from here.

00:06:22.273 --> 00:06:28.584
The size and complexity of a code change should be managed purely for the sake of review.

00:06:28.584 --> 00:06:37.024
Keep diffs small in high-risk areas — authentication, identity, data access, network access, anything that moves money.

00:06:37.024 --> 00:06:51.065
Allow large diffs for code that can be verified empirically: front-end work, back-end plumbing, code with no network or database access, and performance code whose behavior you can measure directly.

00:06:51.065 --> 00:06:59.363
The time it takes to ship software is now completely disconnected from the time it takes to produce the pull request.

00:06:59.363 --> 00:07:07.235
How long the work takes depends entirely on your ability to review and merge code while managing risk at scale.

00:07:07.235 --> 00:07:18.085
So solving the bottlenecks around review matters enormously — linters, testing, continuous integration, shadow-mode verification, empirical verification.

00:07:18.085 --> 00:07:19.929
Agency matters enormously.

00:07:19.929 --> 00:07:26.170
What are the biggest bottlenecks to speeding up the loop, and how do you eliminate them?

00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:30.637
What problems need solving, and when do they need to be solved?

00:07:30.637 --> 00:07:34.183
And what would it take to solve all of them today?

00:07:34.183 --> 00:07:38.155
Deep understanding of the full stack matters enormously.

00:07:38.155 --> 00:07:40.566
Which problems are worth pursuing?

00:07:40.566 --> 00:07:44.537
Is there a higher level of abstraction to address first?

00:07:44.537 --> 00:07:49.927
Should you hand the model the sub-sub-task, the sub-task, or the whole task?

00:07:49.927 --> 00:07:59.288
What are the major risks in a given change — in order of importance: security holes, then correctness holes, then performance holes?

00:07:59.288 --> 00:08:04.040
Is there a faster way to produce the data that lets you merge this?

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:08.366
Should it run in shadow mode, in a sandbox, or behind a flag?

00:08:08.366 --> 00:08:15.954
You may not need to understand every line of logic, but understanding and managing risk matters enormously.

00:08:15.954 --> 00:08:18.932
The cost of complexity itself is changing.

00:08:18.932 --> 00:08:25.741
It might now be worth maintaining fifty percent more code to get a five percent performance win.

00:08:25.741 --> 00:08:33.612
Getting the right abstractions matters less, because large refactors are far less tedious than they used to be.

00:08:33.612 --> 00:08:36.520
Code-quality nitpicks become a huge drag.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:45.243
And very likely a much smarter model will be maintaining your code later — so it's worth taking on more technical debt now.

00:08:45.243 --> 00:08:52.335
Taking the time to hand-architect and rebuild systems today comes with an enormous cost in velocity.

00:08:52.335 --> 00:08:56.590
If it quacks like a duck and walks like a duck, it's a duck.

00:08:56.590 --> 00:09:09.497
For low-risk cases, it may be more sane to treat chunks of code — services, functions — as black boxes, the way we already treat neural networks: do full empirical verification only.

00:09:09.497 --> 00:09:16.234
Has the code produced correct outputs for the last ten, hundred, thousand, ten-thousand inputs?

00:09:16.234 --> 00:09:23.042
Can you quarantine this large piece of code, with no outbound access to the network or database?

00:09:23.042 --> 00:09:29.921
What happens when it's wrong — do you get hacked, do you crash, or is it merely an inconvenience?

00:09:29.921 --> 00:09:32.829
Is it internal-facing or external-facing?

00:09:32.829 --> 00:09:35.878
And what can you do to address those risks?

00:09:35.878 --> 00:09:42.048
Eventually, logical verification — line-by-line review — will come at an enormous cost.

00:09:42.048 --> 00:09:49.140
Save it for where it matters, and build systems that are tolerant of empirical verification instead.

00:09:49.140 --> 00:09:53.537
Is there a decorator that prevents database or network access?

00:09:53.537 --> 00:09:58.217
Correctness bugs are significantly easier to fix than access bugs.

00:09:58.217 --> 00:10:02.827
Finally, what are the rails that allow for even faster iteration?

00:10:02.827 --> 00:10:11.266
Code permissions can be opt-in — database writes, database reads, network egress and to where, access to personal data.

00:10:11.266 --> 00:10:14.528
How long does it take to get shadow-mode data?

00:10:14.528 --> 00:10:17.649
How many pull requests can you test at once?

00:10:17.649 --> 00:10:21.691
And what are the categories of diffs you're dealing with?

00:10:21.691 --> 00:10:23.397
Now the longer arguments.

00:10:23.397 --> 00:10:31.584
The economist Tyler Cowen, writing in The Free Press, on why the government's move is a dangerous turn in AI regulation.

00:10:31.584 --> 00:10:34.109
A new line has been crossed: The U.S.

00:10:34.109 --> 00:10:39.499
government has finally declared an AI model too dangerous for unrestricted use.

00:10:39.499 --> 00:10:43.866
It's the kind of move that could cripple AI progress in the U.S.

00:10:43.866 --> 00:10:45.299
and around the world.

00:10:45.299 --> 00:10:56.966
I had the chance to work with Anthropic's recently released, high-powered Fable 5 model, a version of Claude Mythos (I am a member of Anthropic's Economic Advisory Board).

00:10:56.966 --> 00:10:59.218
But now the plug has been yanked.

00:10:59.218 --> 00:11:09.589
A federal dispute with Anthropic led the government on Friday to order an export control that requires Anthropic to withhold the model from any non-U.S.

00:11:09.589 --> 00:11:10.203
citizens.

00:11:10.203 --> 00:11:16.139
The only practical way to comply with that order was to take down the model altogether.

00:11:16.139 --> 00:11:27.943
Federal officials believed that Fable 5 had been partially "jailbroken," meaning users had figured out how to use it for dangerous purposes that Anthropic meant to restrict.

00:11:27.943 --> 00:11:40.975
For example, Fable 5 was designed not to answer questions about biology (it kicked the queries to Opus 4.8, a less powerful model), so that it could not be used to design dangerous pathogens.

00:11:40.975 --> 00:11:47.388
Fable 5 also would refuse to cooperate if asked to build other, potentially powerful AI tools.

00:11:47.388 --> 00:12:00.079
It is debatable how dangerous a partially jailbroken Fable 5 could be, but the Trump administration expressed concern and claimed that Anthropic was unwilling to apply necessary patches.

00:12:00.079 --> 00:12:07.516
The company does not accept that version of events and claims that the model wasn't jailbroken to begin with.

00:12:07.516 --> 00:12:13.179
Yet the public need not bother too much with whose version of the story is correct.

00:12:13.179 --> 00:12:20.207
What matters is that people had started working with Fable 5, and now they cannot work with it anymore.

00:12:20.207 --> 00:12:28.736
Since Fable 5 had been released only a few days before the order, the interruption of service has been only a modest problem.

00:12:28.736 --> 00:12:37.538
But it is easy to see the problem of dependence here, especially as more and more systems are built around the leading AI models.

00:12:37.538 --> 00:12:40.335
The sad reality is that the more the U.S.

00:12:40.335 --> 00:12:46.885
government decides to deploy a kill switch, the less valuable American AI becomes as a platform.

00:12:46.885 --> 00:12:54.459
Companies will now think twice before relying too heavily on any single AI model that is outside their control.

00:12:54.459 --> 00:13:04.761
Perhaps more importantly, countries will think twice about their AI dependence, knowing that a mere dispute can lead to a major model being taken away.

00:13:04.761 --> 00:13:07.354
In such a world, the power of the U.S.

00:13:07.354 --> 00:13:09.674
government will grow considerably.

00:13:09.674 --> 00:13:14.859
President Donald Trump, for better or worse, already has shown that the U.S.

00:13:14.859 --> 00:13:17.998
can push around other nations if it wishes to.

00:13:17.998 --> 00:13:21.751
That lesson will not be lost on future administrations.

00:13:21.751 --> 00:13:27.073
All of a sudden, "AI sovereignty" is the new catchword, most of all in Europe.

00:13:27.073 --> 00:13:30.962
And who can blame foreign nations for their apprehension?

00:13:30.962 --> 00:13:38.740
Europe is increasingly realizing that it needs to control its own future when it comes to artificial intelligence.

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:41.674
But sovereign AI is not so easy to achieve.

00:13:41.674 --> 00:13:59.277
It requires not only reliable, high-quality domestic models, but also sufficient energy, data centers, grid capacity, a workable permitting process for growth, a good understanding of AI applications, and semiconductor access, among other ancillary services.

00:13:59.277 --> 00:14:05.350
Europe, and indeed most of the rest of the world, is badly behind in most of these areas.

00:14:05.350 --> 00:14:10.740
Having a good and affordable European AI model would not set all of that right.

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:15.653
Many countries do not have much of a chance of achieving AI sovereignty.

00:14:15.653 --> 00:14:24.045
Say you are Peru, which has about 34 million people but is far from being a tech powerhouse, much less a major force in AI.

00:14:24.045 --> 00:14:42.535
Imagine a near future where models from American companies run significant parts of the central bank and much of the education system, manage receipts flowing into the treasury, and are a source of significant and ongoing productivity improvements for Peruvian companies.

00:14:42.535 --> 00:14:51.337
In what sense are we still even talking about Peru here, if so much of the "intelligence" in the country is coming from the U.S.?

00:14:51.337 --> 00:15:00.275
I do not doubt that Peru could end up much richer and better run, but I also am not sure how Peruvians would accept this trade-off.

00:15:00.275 --> 00:15:07.712
Would it suffice to rename Claude as Claudio (or Claudia?), and have it speak Spanish with a Peruvian accent?

00:15:07.712 --> 00:15:11.874
Maybe, but it is fair to say we are in uncharted waters here.

00:15:11.874 --> 00:15:19.516
And Peru, of course, would have to worry about America applying the kill switch to even more of its AI services.

00:15:19.516 --> 00:15:30.842
That could happen as part of an attempt to bully Peru, or it could happen for reasons that have not much to do with Peru, as evidenced by the recent Fable 5 disputes.

00:15:30.842 --> 00:15:37.324
The lack of transparency over the Fable 5 dispute makes this possibility all the more worrying.

00:15:37.324 --> 00:15:43.874
One result is that many countries will be slower to move to even partial reliance on AI systems.

00:15:43.874 --> 00:15:53.904
That will mean lower wealth, lower productivity, and less knowledge and education for much of the world than we would have had with rapid adoption.

00:15:53.904 --> 00:16:01.682
It will be worst for those countries that most need the skills and knowledge that advanced AI systems will confer.

00:16:01.682 --> 00:16:09.597
Another result is that some countries may opt for an alliance with China and Chinese AI models, rather than the U.S.

00:16:09.597 --> 00:16:20.378
At least some of these countries are fence-sitters anyway, when it comes to choosing sides, and so lesser American reliability could tilt a few over the edge.

00:16:20.378 --> 00:16:30.680
In East Africa, for instance, current commercial connections with China are strong, and China has a reputation for not interfering in internal affairs.

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:35.866
In this scenario, America would lose some of its global reach and influence.

00:16:35.866 --> 00:16:43.030
Finally, many countries and companies will opt for open-source AI systems, where there is no kill switch.

00:16:43.030 --> 00:16:49.990
That will also empower Chinese AI over American AI, since the best open-source models come from China.

00:16:49.990 --> 00:17:02.203
That might sound okay, but it is still a big geopolitical loss for America, and possibly for the nations buying Chinese AI as well, if Beijing decides to exploit their dependence.

00:17:02.203 --> 00:17:13.597
Even in the absence of a kill switch, when it comes to servicing, installation, applications, and upgrades, those countries would look to China rather than to the U.S.

00:17:13.597 --> 00:17:20.625
Furthermore, the open-source models typically are worse than the best American-made proprietary models.

00:17:20.625 --> 00:17:22.877
In sum, the inability of the U.S.

00:17:22.877 --> 00:17:29.700
government to reach an agreement with Anthropic translates into a big geopolitical loss for the U.S.

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:36.591
It also means slower and inferior AI adoption for companies, schools, and countries around the world.

00:17:36.591 --> 00:17:47.849
Sometimes I hear non-Americans suggest going "all in" on American AI, conditioned on finding ways to make sure the Americans are equally dependent on others in turn.

00:17:47.849 --> 00:18:04.565
That sounds nice, but given the economic heft and military might of the U.S., I am not sure that many, if any, countries could achieve that status, even if they produce some important components for AI systems, as Germany and the Netherlands do.

00:18:04.565 --> 00:18:09.478
There is yet another huge problem behind all these first-order problems.

00:18:09.478 --> 00:18:18.211
Let us say, for instance, that France's Mistral AI develops very nicely and serves as an EU counterpart of Anthropic and OpenAI.

00:18:18.211 --> 00:18:23.874
Well, then the other European countries will become highly dependent on the French.

00:18:23.874 --> 00:18:33.017
That may seem okay today, but it will be much less fun for the Germans if the French really do have all that extra power and leverage.

00:18:33.017 --> 00:18:38.612
As for the French themselves, they would be highly dependent on a private company.

00:18:38.612 --> 00:18:44.207
France may end up with one such company, but it is unlikely to have three of them.

00:18:44.207 --> 00:18:50.962
So Mistral will in turn have high leverage over France, French politics, and French foreign policy.

00:18:50.962 --> 00:18:53.145
Let us hope they are up to that.

00:18:53.145 --> 00:19:05.563
The simple point is that being influenced by someone in your home country, even if it sounds more appealing rhetorically, is not always better than being pushed around by foreigners.

00:19:05.563 --> 00:19:12.454
Sometimes the foreigners are less oppressive and intrusive, if only because they care less about you.

00:19:12.454 --> 00:19:18.800
The good news is that we probably will get back some safety-enhanced version of Fable 5 soon.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:23.644
The major parties involved all have an incentive to reach an agreement.

00:19:23.644 --> 00:19:34.424
The bad news is that AI sovereignty is a crisis faced by the whole world, yet it is an invisible and slow-moving crisis that is not commanding many headlines.

00:19:34.424 --> 00:19:41.043
It is also a crisis without an easy solution, or one that can be turned into a meaningful slogan.

00:19:41.043 --> 00:19:49.572
"French AI for the French" may sound good, but it raises the questions of how to get there and what to do once you get there.

00:19:49.572 --> 00:19:57.964
We are entering a new world, and we are not prepared to deal with it—or even to think about it in very sophisticated terms.

00:19:57.964 --> 00:20:04.503
And the definitive blow-by-blow: Zvi Mowshowitz, in the second installment of his Fable series.

00:20:04.503 --> 00:20:14.139
The Once And Future Fable 2
On Friday evening the United States Government has forced Anthropic to take down all access to Fable and Mythos.

00:20:14.139 --> 00:20:15.928
It’s been a rough weekend.

00:20:15.928 --> 00:20:16.410
Dean W.

00:20:16.410 --> 00:20:35.820
Ball: One thing about AI regulation being haphazardly imposed on just-released, highly performant models is that in a very real sense, the government just made my world *dumber.* In some impressionistic sense I almost always think this is true of government, but here it is literal.

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:38.022
More details have come to light.

00:20:38.022 --> 00:20:46.832
There remains some fog of war, but we now have a rather good idea why Claude Fable and Mythos were, deeply stupidly, taken down.

00:20:46.832 --> 00:20:53.233
A narrow jailbreak was discovered, of the type Anthropic warned in advance obviously existed.

00:20:53.233 --> 00:21:01.355
All demonstrated outputs are things GPT-5.5 can not only produce, but produce without any sort of jailbreak or bypass.

00:21:01.355 --> 00:21:12.161
The White House demanded Anthropic take down Fable to ‘fix’ the situation, and did not listen when Dario tried to explain that there was no situation to fix.

00:21:12.161 --> 00:21:22.073
When Anthropic did not do so, the White House hit them with an export restriction that they knew would force Fable and Mythos down for everyone.

00:21:22.073 --> 00:21:43.341
A lot of nihilists are justifying this decision, and blaming Anthropic, all of whom are very much confirming that they adhere to Dean Ball’s portrait of the United States Government as a dying NPC hospice patient we have to properly placate with the proper vibes and genuflection so they don’t lash out at us.

00:21:43.341 --> 00:21:50.224
Except they equate this with strength and righteousness, because might makes right, power and vibes.

00:21:50.224 --> 00:21:59.584
This is a fast developing story with a large speed premium, so I apologize for any errors, and for the structure likely not being ideal.

00:21:59.584 --> 00:22:01.099
We do the best we can.

00:22:01.099 --> 00:22:06.811
What we do not know is:
What was motivating the government to make these decisions.

00:22:06.811 --> 00:22:10.804
How deeply they were confused about how any of this works.

00:22:10.804 --> 00:22:15.553
Whether they demanded and are demanding a narrow fix or a global fix.

00:22:15.553 --> 00:22:17.480
Narrow fix is probably easy.

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:19.820
Global fix is probably impossible.

00:22:19.820 --> 00:22:24.432
What they intend to do next and what they are trying to accomplish.

00:22:24.432 --> 00:22:36.064
The good outcome would be that this is a terrible misunderstanding, a reflection of a panic reaction, which can be sorted out quickly, after which we can restore access.

00:22:36.064 --> 00:22:47.765
Or where they otherwise face enough pressure they quickly realize they made a mistake, or Anthropic can do something to quickly assuage their concerns even if it is dumb.

00:22:47.765 --> 00:23:09.446
There will still be a terrible precedent set, which comes with a lot of permanent damage to trust in American AI, to our business climate, to our ability to employ vital foreign AI talent, to America’s relationships to its allies, to the progress of Project Glasswing and our cyber security, and to the rule of law.

00:23:09.446 --> 00:23:21.353
The silver lining, which might be large, is that this will have shown that when we actually need to act, we are not afraid to act, even at great economic and political cost.

00:23:21.353 --> 00:23:31.609
Sometimes there will be a demand driven by national security, or other concerns, and if you cannot physically meet that demand without shutting down?

00:23:31.609 --> 00:23:32.022
Tough.

00:23:32.022 --> 00:23:42.828
This was (with notably extremely rare exceptions) an action far out of bounds of what safety advocates have dared propose as even an option, and it happened.

00:23:42.828 --> 00:23:55.217
So there’s no more saying, in such situations: ‘Give up, the government will never do [X].’
This also emphasizes the need to figure out how to act well, now, before we need to act.

00:23:55.217 --> 00:24:05.403
If we get into such a situation, and don’t have a good way to do [X], we might well do [X] in a no good, haphazard, deeply destructive way, instead.

00:24:05.403 --> 00:24:12.424
So get to work figuring out how to strike deals, or do a pause, or take down a given model, and so on.

00:24:12.424 --> 00:24:21.165
The bad outcome is if this is not a terrible misunderstanding, is motivated by other factors, and cannot be sorted out quickly.

00:24:21.165 --> 00:24:41.126
The government might actually be rapidly escalating towards a forcible takeover of America’s leading AI labs by a would-be authoritarian unitary executive that thinks you should never talk back to it, and when it says jump (or asks for stock, or anything else) everyone should ask how high.

00:24:41.126 --> 00:24:41.676
Or else.

00:24:41.676 --> 00:25:03.082
There is also the third possibility that, as unlikely as it looks now, the White House was correct, the threat was real, and this was an emergency situation, whether or not they did a good job justifying this to Dario and Anthropic in real time, and whether or not they are doing a good job justifying this now.

00:25:03.082 --> 00:25:09.139
Perhaps this was itself dangerous, or perhaps it implied too high risk of other dangers.

00:25:09.139 --> 00:25:13.338
We cannot rule this out until we can verify technical claims.

00:25:13.338 --> 00:25:19.670
And we should not assume that next time, the company will be right and the government wrong.

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:25.796
There likely will come a time when a company says ‘This Is Fine’ and is very, very wrong.

00:25:25.796 --> 00:25:35.156
If that proves to be true, Anthropic will have lost a ton of credibility on all fronts, which is another reason I find this so unlikely.

00:25:35.156 --> 00:25:37.703
They cannot afford to be wrong, here.

00:25:37.703 --> 00:25:50.780
Table of Contents
What Happened When: The Bottom Line
The government’s own account is that Anthropic’s ‘lack of seriousness’ around responding led to the government imposing export controls.

00:25:50.780 --> 00:26:01.105
If we believe Axios and Politico, the ‘lack of seriousness’ was when Anthropic:
Did not rush to take down Fable and act super deferential and serious.

00:26:01.105 --> 00:26:05.923
In response to a jailbreak that did not do anything GPT-5.5 cannot do.

00:26:05.923 --> 00:26:07.643
With no details provided.

00:26:07.643 --> 00:26:10.810
And instead asked for details of the incident.

00:26:10.810 --> 00:26:13.494
Within 90 minutes, on Friday afternoon.

00:26:13.494 --> 00:26:38.066
So it was basically ‘Anthropic wants to only do things because of reasons, and thus we concluded the vibes were off, so f*** them we’re blowing it all up to show who is boss.’
This is also the second time ‘we could not reach Dario this particular minute so we had to blow up all of American AI policy shortly after 5pm on a Friday’ has come up as an excuse.

00:26:38.066 --> 00:26:40.337
It was also used by Emil Michael.

00:26:40.337 --> 00:26:51.212
This time, the claim is that he was at a ‘wellness retreat’ which Anthropic categorically denies, and which Ashlee Vance, who was there, categorically denies.

00:26:51.212 --> 00:27:01.536
Anthropic says it made Dario available 75 minutes after he was requested, and that other senior Anthropic people were made available during that time.

00:27:01.536 --> 00:27:02.569
I believe them.

00:27:02.569 --> 00:27:13.237
The White House waited far longer than 75 minutes, indeed they waited overnight, after they were contacted by Amazon, to start attempting to contact Dario.

00:27:13.237 --> 00:27:19.294
Amazon Calls The White House
Details continue to come in on the events and the timeline.

00:27:19.294 --> 00:27:39.323
First Axios:
Maria Curi (Axios):
Behind the scenes: Amazon called administration officials Thursday night to share a report showing how they were able to jailbreak and access portions of Anthropic’s powerful new Mythos model that pose a national security threat, sources familiar told Axios.

00:27:39.323 --> 00:27:54.466
Anthropic had previously notified the government multiple times about the planned June 9 release of Fable — which is a general-use version of Mythos —and the government did not object, a source close to the company said.

00:27:54.466 --> 00:28:08.232
But calls from Amazon — as well as at least five other companies to a variety of senior administration officials Thursday evening and Friday morning — led to the model being shut down by Friday night.

00:28:08.232 --> 00:28:18.005
Amazon is confirmed as the central call, among others, that caused the White House to start taking actions that led to them taking down Fable.

00:28:18.005 --> 00:28:27.985
As I discussed last time, Anthropic’s release announcement included clear warnings that jailbreaks on the level of what Amazon did were possible.

00:28:27.985 --> 00:28:33.216
I have no doubt they extensively briefed the administration on such details.

00:28:33.216 --> 00:28:38.103
Does anyone remember this graph, from the Fable 5 release announcement?

00:28:38.103 --> 00:28:42.921
I do not understand why Amazon’s CEO called the White House over this.

00:28:42.921 --> 00:28:47.189
There is a key piece of information there that we do not know.

00:28:47.189 --> 00:29:02.193
The Government Panics
Anthropic was then given less than 24 hours from the initial call by Amazon, and no details of anything actually concerning happening, after which it was hit by a classic ‘Friday after 5pm’ order.

00:29:02.193 --> 00:29:09.558
For most of those less than 24 hours, the government had not yet attempted to contact Anthropic about this.

00:29:09.558 --> 00:29:25.113
We have a source in the White House confirming, even if we fully buy their story, that they decided to risk blowing up all of American AI because they did not like the vibes they got in 90 minutes over a series of phone calls.

00:29:25.113 --> 00:29:49.548
Sophia C and Cheyenne Haslett: The move, which followed multiple tense calls between Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei and administration officials, including Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent and White House Cyber Director Sean Cairncross, underscores how the White House is wrestling in real-time with regulating fast-moving and potentially dangerous AI models.

00:29:49.548 --> 00:30:04.965
… Following the meeting, the administration attempted to reach Amodei but was told he was unavailable because he was attending a wellness retreat, one of the administration officials and the senior White House official said.

00:30:04.965 --> 00:30:23.136
A spokesperson for Anthropic rejected the claim that he was at a wellness retreat, saying, “this is absolutely false.”
A person close to Anthropic said Amodei was first requested around noon and was on the phone with senior officials within an hour and 15 minutes.

00:30:23.136 --> 00:30:29.812
While he was out of pocket, Anthropic offered other senior leaders in his place, the person said.

00:30:29.812 --> 00:30:51.080
When the administration finally reached Amodei, he participated in three calls with a combination of roughly half a dozen senior administration officials, including Cairncross, Bessent and Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick, according to the senior White House official and one of the administration officials.

00:30:51.080 --> 00:30:56.862
… During the calls, Amodei tried to clear up what he assumed was a misunderstanding.

00:30:56.862 --> 00:31:17.235
He pushed back on the administration’s concerns, defended the guardrails and argued that the type of bypass that occurred, which he believed to be specific, did not pose the same risk as a broader “jailbreak” that would allow it to be used without any of the guardrails put in place by Anthropic.

00:31:17.235 --> 00:31:27.284
Dario tried to explain that this was a narrow issue, and they simply did not understand or believe him, or chose not to understand or believe him.

00:31:27.284 --> 00:31:32.791
We now know that Dario was fully correct that the issue was narrow and harmless.

00:31:32.791 --> 00:31:42.771
Where Dario was incorrect was in assuming those he was talking to were both capable of and interested in understanding what he was trying to say.

00:31:42.771 --> 00:31:56.674
They urged Anthropic to voluntarily remove the model and coordinate with the government to address the vulnerabilities, according to the senior White House official and the two administration officials.

00:31:56.674 --> 00:32:11.679
Amodei asked for more time and information, but he made no commitments to pull the model, and at one point Bessent told Amodei directly that he was making a “bad decision,” according to the senior White House official.

00:32:11.679 --> 00:32:20.076
… “Export controls were a last resort after begging them for hours to work with us,” the senior White House official said.

00:32:20.076 --> 00:32:34.668
“This was not something we wanted to do, but our hands were tied.”
After publication, one of the people close to Anthropic disputed that the company was given a choice to voluntarily work with the administration.

00:32:34.668 --> 00:32:42.446
“The White House gave 90 minutes to take the models down, with no details on the actual threat,” the person said.

00:32:42.446 --> 00:33:17.204
“There was never any begging — or asking — for them to work with us, just a declared 90 minute deadline.”
tae kim: FT confirms: "Anthropic was given 90 minutes to comply and was not provided with detailed concerns before the order was issued, according to a person close to the company."
Do you think the White House was ‘begging for hours?’ Or do you think they’re just throwing words out, that at best are code for ‘we did not issue an official order yet?’
I see no reason not to believe Anthropic here.

00:33:17.204 --> 00:33:22.435
Dario tried to explain that this was a false positive and asked for details.

00:33:22.435 --> 00:33:30.695
The White House did not provide any details that supported their claims, or evidence that this was necessary or prudent.

00:33:30.695 --> 00:33:46.456
They simply said ‘remove Fable in 90 minutes,’ likely without making it clear this was ‘or else IFAR.’
What pissed them off, it seems, is in large part that Anthropic wanted reasons, rather than asking how high when told to jump.

00:33:46.456 --> 00:33:51.412
That he failed to commit to asking how high, in general, no matter what.

00:33:51.412 --> 00:34:02.838
Axios: The bottom line: The source familiar with the government’s thinking said there was a “lack of seriousness” that Anthropic was applying to the release of Fable.

00:34:02.838 --> 00:34:18.393
“Had Anthropic taken it seriously and, rather than dismissing as isolated, moved to fix or pause access, this would have never happened,” the source said, adding “they were overly confident.”
As in, they told us we were wrong.

00:34:18.393 --> 00:34:20.595
That means they are not serious.

00:34:20.595 --> 00:34:26.377
How could they possibly understand the situation better than the Treasury Secretary?

00:34:26.377 --> 00:34:28.098
Catch up quick: At 1 p.m.

00:34:28.098 --> 00:34:43.584
ET on Friday, Anthropic received a call from the government instructing them to roll back the release of the Mythos and Fable models due to a “national security threat,” but with no further details, the Anthropic source said.

00:34:43.584 --> 00:34:54.459
“We immediately sought to understand the specific nature of the threat so we could remediate it,” the source said, but the government held firm on the demand.

00:34:54.459 --> 00:35:08.294
Anthropic source: The Trump administration gave Anthropic 90 minutes on Friday to pull down its most powerful models before imposing a licensing regime on the company, according to an Anthropic source.

00:35:08.294 --> 00:35:11.253
Miles Brundage: Sure sounds like a hit job.

00:35:11.253 --> 00:35:14.626
The Stupider Version
And that’s the good version.

00:35:14.626 --> 00:35:31.420
The bad version, as Chubby explains here, and which Axios seems to make clear, is that the White House is simply being petty, and thinks Anthropic ‘screwed them’ by asking for reasons and by having employed people with opposing political views.

00:35:31.420 --> 00:35:34.999
That is very illustrative of how these people think.

00:35:34.999 --> 00:35:43.396
Why it matters: Governing the world's most consequential technology is coming down to speaking President Trump's language.

00:35:43.396 --> 00:35:58.814
Anthropic failed to "honor" a recent cyber executive order, administration officials claim, and the company's purported failure to take the matter seriously led to its most powerful products being scrubbed from the internet.

00:35:58.814 --> 00:36:01.705
"Everybody said Anthropic was a bad actor.

00:36:01.705 --> 00:36:05.146
Some of us said it was time to give them a chance.

00:36:05.146 --> 00:36:07.762
Now those people are questioning that.

00:36:07.762 --> 00:36:11.203
They screwed us," an administration official said.

00:36:11.203 --> 00:36:25.176
…
Behind the scenes: "Anthropic has not done a great job at trying to speak to the administration and appreciate the ideological differences," one source familiar with the administration's thinking said.

00:36:25.176 --> 00:36:36.463
"It's like they just speak in different languages," the source said, adding that the company has simply not figured out how to communicate with this administration.

00:36:36.463 --> 00:36:49.059
…
Even before this breakdown, a previous fight between Anthropic and the Pentagon also came down in some ways to just not liking the person on the other side of the negotiating table.

00:36:49.059 --> 00:37:01.104
A White House official told Axios that the Pentagon fight is completely unrelated — but Anthropic's inability to communicate effectively showed up in a similar, unhelpful way.

00:37:01.104 --> 00:37:03.307
"We never wanted this to happen.

00:37:03.307 --> 00:37:09.777
Our number one priority is innovation but our hands were tied," the White House official said.

00:37:09.777 --> 00:37:12.117
The optics added fuel to the fire.

00:37:12.117 --> 00:37:16.591
Anthropic came out with a blog post dismissing the Amazon report.

00:37:16.591 --> 00:37:27.879
Then the company enlisted a cybersecurity expert viewed by the administration as a "radical Democrat," who was then celebrated by Chris Krebs, who Trump just fired.

00:37:27.879 --> 00:37:41.025
The White House did not like that the Anthropic security expert was a ‘radical Democrat’ and the White House is interpreting that as ‘they screwed us’ and should now be considered bad actors.

00:37:41.025 --> 00:37:45.292
The stupidity, on all sides, of such a thing, knows no bounds.

00:37:45.292 --> 00:37:52.175
This is not something that should matter, but it also would be a really stupid mistake by Anthropic.

00:37:52.175 --> 00:38:10.759
Look, yes, these folks are that obsessed with political perspectives, so when dealing with them directly you really do need to prioritize sending in people who won’t set off these folks, even though this is a fully apolitical situation where that concern makes no sense.

00:38:10.759 --> 00:38:12.686
So it’s kind of on everyone.

00:38:12.686 --> 00:38:20.464
There Was No Wellness Retreat
Ashlee Vance: Anthropic has pushed AI forward dramatically over the past two years.

00:38:20.464 --> 00:38:23.561
It’s currently the crown jewel of US AI tech.

00:38:23.561 --> 00:38:28.379
The Feds don’t like DarioAmodei because he won’t do all their bidding.

00:38:28.379 --> 00:38:42.420
