Think about what you are saying.

00:48:22.785 --> 00:48:36.826
That’s on top of the people saying ‘Anthropic said government should regulate AI so this serves them right’ or ‘Anthropic said that frontier models are dangerous so this serves them right.’ Similar vibes.

00:48:36.826 --> 00:48:47.632
Whereas for those of us who are not nihilists, who do not believe in might makes right, it is hard to see the reasonable version of this from the USGov side.

00:48:47.632 --> 00:49:00.296
The correct criticism of Anthropic is ‘they should have still taken the model down when ordered, no matter how stupid they thought that was, while discussions continued.’ That’s valid.

00:49:00.296 --> 00:49:04.013
The things people are almost entirely actually saying?

00:49:04.013 --> 00:49:16.127
It’s a bunch of nihilism, of pure worshipping of power and tribalism, and hurting everyone as long as it hurts those you dislike more, of lashing out because of and with vibes.

00:49:16.127 --> 00:49:22.735
Mostly Harmless
At least one source has now seen the research report, claiming it shows nothing.

00:49:22.735 --> 00:49:31.545
We don’t have any person on the other side claiming that the report shows something, or explaining what that something might be.

00:49:31.545 --> 00:49:49.509
Katie Moussouris (CEO Luta Security): The government’s response “seems way out of line with what’s actually in the research report.”
All AI models need to be able to help defenders in exactly this way, or we won’t be able to scale our defense against attackers.

00:49:49.509 --> 00:50:02.518
Maria Curi: Moussouris said the researchers were able to find security vulnerabilities by asking questions normal defenders would ask AI, which is exactly what the model was intended to do.

00:50:02.518 --> 00:50:09.814
Everyone Means Everyone
It looks like when Anthropic took Mythos down, they really did fully take it down.

00:50:09.814 --> 00:50:20.069
The Economist: Spy agencies are likely to regain access to Mythos, says one former British intelligence official; negotiations are already under way.

00:50:20.069 --> 00:50:22.340
Private firms may find it harder.

00:50:22.340 --> 00:50:28.328
Even so, some observers believe the American government will eventually have to relent.

00:50:28.328 --> 00:50:35.624
It appears that, because this was done in such a stupid fashion, Project Glasswing is cut off from Mythos.

00:50:35.624 --> 00:50:39.754
The clock is ticking before others get similar capabilities.

00:50:39.754 --> 00:50:44.641
I wonder what the spy agencies and major corporations think about this.

00:50:44.641 --> 00:51:00.816
The ‘good’ news is that Mythos has presumably already found a lot more vulnerabilities that remain unpatched, and which Claude Opus 4.8 and GPT-5.5 are strong enough to help patch once they are found, so defensive work should continue.

00:51:00.816 --> 00:51:12.998
Cyber leaders, according to Axios, are being clear that this move net harms our cyber security, because given who has access in what ways it helps defenders more than attackers.

00:51:12.998 --> 00:51:19.399
There is now an open letter to this effect, urging the government to restore access to Fable.

00:51:19.399 --> 00:51:59.595
Kevin Frazier (via Axios): “Prominent cybersecurity leaders — including CISOs, security researchers and executives at Adobe, Zoom and Sophos — are urging the Trump administration to reverse restrictions on Anthropic's most advanced AI models, arguing the move hurts cyber defenders more than attackers.”
From the letter, calling this a pure unforced error that does nothing but net damage:
It is our understanding that underlying model capabilities in the original research that triggered this action:
Were focused on determining whether a human-prompted section of code was insecure.

00:51:59.595 --> 00:52:08.887
This is a necessary capability in any model that is intended to write secure code and should not be considered an offensive capability.

00:52:08.887 --> 00:52:14.462
Can be replicated on GPT-5.5, Opus, Sonnet and even Chinese models like Kimi 2.7.

00:52:14.462 --> 00:52:30.155
The justification for this unprecedented action was that Fable provides a unique “uplift” of capabilities beyond other AI models, but AI has been finding bugs and generating working exploits at superhuman levels since last year.

00:52:30.155 --> 00:52:32.702
Anthropic is addressing the research.

00:52:32.702 --> 00:52:47.913
As security professionals, we recognize that our work does not lead to a simple end-state where a system is fully safe, and the purpose of research like this is to enable continuous improvement, not to ban the technology.

00:52:47.913 --> 00:52:59.683
As a result, this action has taken the best models away from defenders, created market uncertainty, and risked America’s AI leadership without any real risk to justify it.

00:52:59.683 --> 00:53:18.129
This Could Be The Good Scenario And Mostly A Misunderstanding
The action was definitely ‘vibe governing.’ The decision was some combination of ‘this seems vaguely spooky’ and ‘f*** Anthropic,’ not ‘we have a policy and a threshold.’
It could still be well intentioned.

00:53:18.129 --> 00:53:27.834
Nathan Lambert: The Dario faction and the Sacks faction speak very different languages, and a Dario clarification could sound like a refusal.

00:53:27.834 --> 00:53:31.000
This puts us very squarely in vibe governance.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:38.021
Models are released when the gov thinks its okay, and it is unlikely this is based on technical evals.

00:53:38.021 --> 00:53:42.426
My presumption is that what happened was pretty straightforward.

00:53:42.426 --> 00:53:59.771
Someone said ‘hey there is a jailbreak fix it’ and Dario said ‘this is harmless there is nothing to fix.’ The question remains, was the request ‘fix this particular jailbreak’ or ‘fix all jailbreaks pls tks?’
The above is the charitable interpretation.

00:53:59.771 --> 00:54:02.180
There is also the uncharitable one.

00:54:02.180 --> 00:54:21.727
Ben Smith: Extent to which White House allies are signaling that this is a culture war issue, not a technical one, is striking
Matthew Yglesias: I would say they’re not even signaling that it’s a culture war issue, they’re signaling that it’s a “pay us money or else” shakedown issue.

00:54:21.727 --> 00:54:36.456
There’s no content at all to this, it’s just gangster politics
Taylor Budowich: I’m told Anthropic is perplexed by the situation they are facing, so they’ve turned to k8em0 to do their on-the-record rapid response.

00:54:36.456 --> 00:54:39.072
These people really just don’t get it.

00:54:39.072 --> 00:55:04.332
Or simply:
Miles Brundage: “Well acktually Dario seems smug so abusing government authorities is fine” - some of y’all basically
Kudos to Martin Casado for speaking out against what happened, and maybe even being convinced by argument to move from his initial position of ‘it’s a cyber weapon so any jailbreak is unacceptable’ even if he did end up blocking that guy.

00:55:04.332 --> 00:55:30.005
I will fully allow some amount of ‘Anthropic’s rhetoric did not make this easier’ if it is coupled with ‘and bad decisions are still bad’ rather than ‘so f*** Anthropic even if we all lose.’
The Next Step
Anthropic is flying various senior technical staff to Washington, who are spending today trying to sort this all out, which is absolutely what you do in this situation.

00:55:30.005 --> 00:55:32.277
We will soon learn how that goes.

00:55:32.277 --> 00:55:34.273
Many next steps are possible.

00:55:34.273 --> 00:55:41.431
The Worst Licensing Regime Is Fully Ad-Hoc
We now have more or less the worst possible licensing regime.

00:55:41.431 --> 00:55:52.650
It is fully ad-hoc, vibes based, and based on the whims of people who do not understand how AI works, and who we have no reason to assume are acting in good faith.

00:55:52.650 --> 00:55:53.132
Dean W.

00:55:53.132 --> 00:55:58.913
Ball: Make no mistake: post-Mythos, the United States has a licensing regime for AI.

00:55:58.913 --> 00:56:05.934
It’s just informal, with no consistent rules or firm boundaries on state power or public transparency.

00:56:05.934 --> 00:56:12.610
Cobalt mining in the Congo is vastly more institutionalized than frontier AI licensing in the US.

00:56:12.610 --> 00:56:20.732
If you avoid all formal regulations and laws, and this results in regulation and law via executive fiat, that’s worse.

00:56:20.732 --> 00:56:23.003
You know that that’s worse right?

00:56:23.003 --> 00:56:26.307
Neil Chilson and Adam Thierer: This is not good!

00:56:26.307 --> 00:56:27.271
A leading U.S.

00:56:27.271 --> 00:56:37.044
AI company was forced to take down a product that millions were using based on non-public, unexplained concerns of a few government officials.

00:56:37.044 --> 00:56:39.798
This isn’t the red-tape risk of the FDA.

00:56:39.798 --> 00:56:50.810
It’s more like the FDA demanding, out of the blue and without explanation, that everyone stop drinking milk — if milk was 50% of last year’s stock market gains.

00:56:50.810 --> 00:56:59.896
… But even if you disagree with Anthropic’s regulatory strategy, this escalation of government intervention is nothing to celebrate.

00:56:59.896 --> 00:57:02.924
It is horrible for the broader AI ecosystem.

00:57:02.924 --> 00:57:13.730
Continued arbitrary, unexplained deployment of export control authority will make companies slow-walk new models, depriving the public of powerful new tools.

00:57:13.730 --> 00:57:20.131
Every AI model, like all software before it, will have vulnerabilities that require patching.

00:57:20.131 --> 00:57:28.528
The US government should not hang a Sword of Damocles over every lab’s head, with no indication when it might drop or why.

00:57:28.528 --> 00:57:32.176
… This episode yet again shows why Congress must act.

00:57:32.176 --> 00:57:41.881
We need a balanced statutory framework for frontier model safety, rooted in the rule of law, with clear standards and transparent procedures.

00:57:41.881 --> 00:57:49.177
Civilian authorities must direct this process; it must not be co-opted by the military-industrial complex.

00:57:49.177 --> 00:57:58.125
America’s AI leadership will diminish if our government continues the ad-hoc and myopic approach to AI policy recently on display.

00:57:58.125 --> 00:57:58.813
Well said.

00:57:58.813 --> 00:58:16.020
What the White House is doing is terrible no matter your view on future AI capabilities, or AI risks, or the need to ‘win the AI race.’ It is bad all around, except that it centralizes power within the White House, via the threat of ad hoc shutdowns.

00:58:16.020 --> 00:58:24.211
Remember when Trump was worried that a proposed Executive Order would harm American AI too much, so he did not sign it?

00:58:24.211 --> 00:58:29.304
This is so, so much worse for that, while also having many other problems.

00:58:29.304 --> 00:58:46.718
Mark Dalton at R Street has a similar analysis, calling this The Fable Fiasco: A Bad Idea Applied Badly, pointing out that ITAR and KYC are not equipped for this task, and pointing out we will face real foreign-policy consequences for doing it this way.

00:58:46.718 --> 00:59:03.030
We Are Showing We Are Unreliable Partners
As mentioned last time, but it bears repeating: One of those other problems is that this gives a huge kick to those who previously thought they were our allies and would be under our AI umbrella.

00:59:03.030 --> 00:59:06.678
Do not forget that the European Union still has ASML.

00:59:06.678 --> 00:59:14.800
Not only will such folks not trust the ‘American AI stack’ under these conditions, they will try to build a rival one.

00:59:14.800 --> 00:59:29.392
This risks driving them into the hands of China, and towards having their own chips and their own data centers under their own control, and towards use of non-American open models even though they are much worse.

00:59:29.392 --> 00:59:32.833
Tyler Cowen: A new line has been crossed: The U.S.

00:59:32.833 --> 00:59:38.271
government has finally declared an AI model too dangerous for unrestricted use.

00:59:38.271 --> 00:59:42.676
It’s the kind of move that could cripple AI progress in the U.S.

00:59:42.676 --> 00:59:44.121
and around the world.

00:59:44.121 --> 00:59:48.457
The events here also do not bode well for American open models.

00:59:48.457 --> 01:00:14.199
If America is willing to put export controls on not only model weights but the model outputs, even when they are as heavily safeguarded as Fable, do you think they are not coming for your open models, with no classifiers that are not easily removed, with no safety training that cannot be undone by anyone who knows about obliteratus, that cannot be shut down once released?

01:00:14.199 --> 01:00:18.123
Think harder about the implications of what is happening.

01:00:18.123 --> 01:00:22.321
Our policy responses are going off the rails remarkably fast.

01:00:22.321 --> 01:00:33.058
So I will close with a reminder of how badly we need rule of law, here, and how bad the alternative is already proving to be only weeks into the new regime.

01:00:33.058 --> 01:00:33.540
Dean W.

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:40.630
Ball: AI policy is a really poignant example of just how deeply American civics have been hollowed out.

01:00:40.630 --> 01:00:48.063
In almost all other areas of tech policy, we have at least some prior law and regulation from which to draw.

01:00:48.063 --> 01:00:58.938
If you think, as I do, that politics and law are ritual practices through which we embody civic ideals, these earlier bodies of law are like prior ritual art.

01:00:58.938 --> 01:01:01.967
They give us some sense of a starting point.

01:01:01.967 --> 01:01:12.084
So even though crypto is new, it is part of a very old industry (financial services), which carries with it a lot of prior legal and political art.

01:01:12.084 --> 01:01:18.485
With AI we have nothing of the sort, so all our leaders can think to do is punch one another.

01:01:18.485 --> 01:01:29.429
The impulse of “let’s have stable rules so that we aren’t punching one another all the time” isn’t really something you hear anyone saying outside of industry.

01:01:29.429 --> 01:01:34.041
The rule of law seems absent in our political muscle memory.Dean W.

01:01:34.041 --> 01:01:44.847
Ball: Precisely as I predicted, the recent cyber EO, which admin officials insisted was not a licensing regime, ends up in practice being a licensing regime.

01:01:44.847 --> 01:02:01.641
Forget “voluntary,” forget “permissionless.”
AI is licensed now, but the requirements change constantly and are always a secret, even to the administration itself, which will discover the rules spontaneously in real time as it reacts to events.

01:02:01.641 --> 01:02:10.795
This means also that the rules are in practice stricter and more roughly enforced for organizations the administration does not like.

01:02:10.795 --> 01:02:14.512
Can you blame Anthropic for making itself so disliked?

01:02:14.512 --> 01:02:15.682
In a sense, sure.

01:02:15.682 --> 01:02:23.322
The problem is that this childish “he said, she said” is all we have to go on in our analysis of the situation.

01:02:23.322 --> 01:02:35.230
And because there is no transparency (it is all calls and texts between “White House officials” and “Anthropic executives”), in practice it comes down to who you trust more.

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:37.088
This is why we create laws!

01:02:37.088 --> 01:02:48.582
To abstract away from personal power struggles and grudges, to submit to the steady application of rules so that complex human activity can unfold with predictability.

01:02:48.582 --> 01:02:51.955
The rule of law has been being eroded in the U.S.

01:02:51.955 --> 01:03:05.101
for my entire life, but it is especially acute in AI because of both the lack of much preexisting law to serve as bulwark, and because of this admin’s insistence that it is Not Regulating AI.

01:03:05.101 --> 01:03:14.600
This has become an excuse for vagueness and evasiveness in rule-drafting (see the cyber EO), and this in turn makes the lawlessness worse.

01:03:14.600 --> 01:03:19.762
The government wants to apply its force to frontier AI, that much is clear.

01:03:19.762 --> 01:03:22.308
It wants to make the industry submit.

01:03:22.308 --> 01:03:34.560
And in service of that goal, it has discovered that “not regulating AI” is in fact a great excuse for refusing to support laws that could constrain the admin’s exercise of power.

01:03:34.560 --> 01:03:41.649
In other words, “not regulating AI” is a *justification* for the tyrannical control of AI by the state.

01:03:41.649 --> 01:03:45.641
This should alarm you regardless of what party you are in.

01:03:45.641 --> 01:03:53.006
What you are seeing now will be used against you one day soon, if not by this admin then by its successors.

01:03:53.006 --> 01:03:55.897
This is the antithesis of the rule of law.

01:03:55.897 --> 01:04:00.164
The administration cannot and will not fix this problem alone.

01:04:00.164 --> 01:04:04.156
We need Congress to step in and impose rules on this mess.

01:04:04.156 --> 01:04:07.102
From the shutdown to the work itself.

01:04:07.102 --> 01:04:13.471
James Pethokoukis introduces what he calls the world's top AI-pilled economists.

01:04:13.471 --> 01:04:23.343
Meet the world’s top AI-pilled economists

"This year the NBER is likely to host more conferences on health care than on AI.

01:04:23.343 --> 01:04:29.234
But some academic economists have seized the AI opportunity."
TheEconomist

01:04:29.234 --> 01:04:34.027
Ethan Mollick, on the big issue with AI strategies at large companies.

01:04:34.027 --> 01:04:53.197
Big issue with AI strategies at big companies which realized the importance of AI last year (which is only a small subset, most are still not moving fast) is that, in the best case, they developed their strategy in late 2025, before the agentic revolution

Things changed since...

01:04:53.197 --> 01:04:59.280
And Mollick at length, on what it actually feels like to work with a model like Mythos.

01:04:59.280 --> 01:05:12.216
What it feels like to work with Mythos
Claude Fable represents another big jump in AI
I had early access to the first Mythos-class AI model being released to the public, Claude 5 Fable.

01:05:12.216 --> 01:05:27.459
Much of the discussion of Mythos has centered on its impact on software security, but I tested it on everything except that (the guardrails around Fable essentially prevent it from being used for cybersecurity at all).

01:05:27.459 --> 01:05:39.975
My conclusion is that it represents a very real leap over every model I have used before, and, maybe more important, suggests our relationship with AI is changing in drastic ways.

01:05:39.975 --> 01:05:41.724
First, how good is Fable?

01:05:41.724 --> 01:05:50.953
In experiment after experiment I conducted, it outperformed basically every other public model I have used by a considerable margin.

01:05:50.953 --> 01:06:01.232
It was capable across many problems and produced some startling results — it would work up to a dozen hours executing on multi-page specifications.

01:06:01.232 --> 01:06:11.930
I’ll walk you through a couple of more complex, and serious, use cases shortly, but you could see the general improvement across the board on every task.

01:06:11.930 --> 01:06:22.838
The problem about communicating this in a post is that many of the most impressive results are going to be interesting to only small portions of my readers.

01:06:22.838 --> 01:06:33.187
For example, it made the most sophisticated academic social science paper I have yet seen from an AI from a single prompt and one piece of feedback.

01:06:33.187 --> 01:06:40.319
It also created a 10-page epic rhyming poem about a haircut where every word starts with the letter s.

01:06:40.319 --> 01:06:47.381
So, as a more accessible and entertaining example, I also had it create a bunch of games you can try.

01:06:47.381 --> 01:07:03.044
All of these are one initial prompt in Claude Code where Fable had to take my vague prompts and generate something workable, followed by a couple of additional prompts with minor encouragement (“make it better”) or feedback.

01:07:03.044 --> 01:07:14.861
What makes these especially impressive is that Claude cannot generate images, so every piece of art or 3D object was made with math alone, not using any external assets.

01:07:14.861 --> 01:07:32.761
You can try any of them: a game about flipping coins (prompt: “Balatro, but for the game of coin flips”) that is quite fun; a snake game where the snake is self-aware and crazy things happen; or a game about descending into the depths to see what is there.

01:07:32.761 --> 01:07:34.719
So the output is impressive.

01:07:34.719 --> 01:07:43.739
But, especially as I turned to more serious projects, I often felt using the tool was somewhere between delightful and unnerving.

01:07:43.739 --> 01:07:48.005
Delightful because I just asked for something at it happened.

01:07:48.005 --> 01:07:52.899
And also unnerving because I just asked for something and it happened.

01:07:52.899 --> 01:08:06.954
Maps and Methods
To see why, it helps to understand the way in which Fable gets work done, and for that I want to turn to an example I have tested on many previous AI models: building an isochrone map.

01:08:06.954 --> 01:08:17.512
This is a map that shows the distance you can travel in a given length of time, and the first one was created in 1881 showing travel times from London.

01:08:17.512 --> 01:08:31.916
No previous model did an even halfway useful job with trying to create a map like this because it involves researching thousands of potential trip distances and a lot of small judgement calls and decisions.

01:08:31.916 --> 01:08:46.950
I decided to try it on Fable using Claude Code with this prompt: i want you to build a fully researched and beautiful isochronic map that lets me pick various cities and see real isochronic lines based on real data.

01:08:46.950 --> 01:08:49.117
I want the design to be unique.

01:08:49.117 --> 01:08:56.249
You should take into account airports (and travel time to and from airports) trains, walking, driving.

01:08:56.249 --> 01:09:02.193
The data does not need to be live but should be real based on your research and data.

01:09:02.193 --> 01:09:09.115
You can start with a few cities but more general is better, this should be an entirely new project.

01:09:09.115 --> 01:09:13.800
It then suggested that it do this in the style of the original map.

01:09:13.800 --> 01:09:15.828
I agreed, and it got to work.

01:09:15.828 --> 01:09:26.806
It is worth a second looking at the transcript of the multiple hour building session the AI went through on its own, because you can see some unusual things.

01:09:26.806 --> 01:09:47.993
First, the AI launched multiple other AIs (I believe mostly the cheaper Claude Sonnet) to help it conduct research on travel times, ultimately retrieving over 2,200 specific flights, the rail schedules for trains from the TGV to the Shinkansen, and road speeds per country from multiple academic papers.

01:09:47.993 --> 01:09:51.838
And while those agents were running, it started coding.

01:09:51.838 --> 01:09:59.460
Then it launched yet more agents and tests to verify its code, all the while taking notes about its progress.

01:09:59.460 --> 01:10:09.739
The result was a fully functioning map of impressive sophistication that looked a lot like the 1881 original, but that doesn’t mean it was perfect.

01:10:09.739 --> 01:10:25.961
I noticed that a lot of remote locations (like Greenland) just contained estimates of travel time, not exact numbers, so I told Fable to fix it, including the instructions: actually get travel times to remote airports and locations.

01:10:25.961 --> 01:10:34.072
This time the AI launched a workflow, adversarial groups of agents that did research and tested each others results.

01:10:34.072 --> 01:10:41.903
It figured out how often ships sail to Pitcairn Island in the Pacific and how to get to Grise Fjord from Ottawa.

01:10:41.903 --> 01:10:48.406
And it used a tremendous number of tokens in a very short period of time (more on this soon).

01:10:48.406 --> 01:10:50.364
The results were impressive.

01:10:50.364 --> 01:10:58.685
I pushed a few more times in directions that interested me (including asking for other visualization approaches, etc.).

01:10:58.685 --> 01:11:08.544
I would recommend spending a couple minutes clicking around the results, and you can read its methods and sources at the bottom of the graph.

01:11:08.544 --> 01:11:24.277
This is probably not a useful project for you unless you really like travel and maps, but it is indicative of AI solving a hard problem involving research, math, visual development, taste, judgement, complex coding, and more.

01:11:24.277 --> 01:11:27.423
And, the unnerving part was how little I did.

01:11:27.423 --> 01:11:31.479
I gave a really ambitious instruction, the AI followed it.

01:11:31.479 --> 01:11:36.443
I gave a couple of minor pieces of feedback, and the AI figured it out.

01:11:36.443 --> 01:11:38.541
My role was extremely limited.

01:11:38.541 --> 01:11:55.392
Importantly, it was just limited in how much work I did relative to the model, it was also limited in how much control I had over how the model did things, why the model chose particular approaches, or even how in-depth its results would be.

01:11:55.392 --> 01:12:03.923
The details of the AI’s decision making are not shown to me, and the process would be too long to even be worth following.

01:12:03.923 --> 01:12:16.020
The map required the AI to make judgement calls about hundreds of little choices, and it just made them, without me understanding the choices or having a chance to weigh in.

01:12:16.020 --> 01:12:24.760
In many ways, it is miraculous (I can always ask for edits at the end) on the other, it turns AI into the ultimate black box.

01:12:24.760 --> 01:12:32.452
Working with a Mythos-class model
The most ambitious project I got from Fable takes a little more explanation.

01:12:32.452 --> 01:12:43.569
I do a lot of research where humans produce messy answers and doing any sort of analysis requires categorize those answers properly: how innovative is an idea?

01:12:43.569 --> 01:12:45.597
why do people like this book?

01:12:45.597 --> 01:12:59.372
To figure this out, we used human researchers to make a judgement call about a piece of information, and statistically compare their answers with others to figure out whether we can trust the data.

01:12:59.372 --> 01:13:10.350
A lot of recent research has shown that AIs might be able to do this important work, but calibrating AI and human judgement has been difficult and expensive.

01:13:10.350 --> 01:13:18.181
So I asked Fable to solve the problem, first generating a complex 19 page design document and then executing it.

01:13:18.181 --> 01:13:20.699
It worked for nine and a half hours.

01:13:20.699 --> 01:13:35.243
The result was an extremely sophisticated piece of software the AI called Concord that could take in multiple datasets, calibrate human and AI responses, and then conduct complex data analysis on the results.

01:13:35.243 --> 01:13:36.991
Again, it wasn’t perfect.

01:13:36.991 --> 01:13:46.360
As an expert, I was able to spot some errors and omissions (some as a result of the design I had asked for) that I had the AI correct.

01:13:46.360 --> 01:13:53.353
But the scope of the delivery on this project, and many others, exceeded anything I had seen before.

01:13:53.353 --> 01:14:01.394
In this case, it was a piece of software that researchers have needed for years but was never profitable to create.

01:14:01.394 --> 01:14:04.540
You can now just use or modify the code here.

01:14:04.540 --> 01:14:25.447
I am sure it is not perfect (I only spent an hour working with the results), but a software engineer would iron out the remaining potential bugs that I could not find quickly (which is one reason we may need more, not less, coders in the future, to help with the explosion of new uses for software).

01:14:25.447 --> 01:14:29.433
This power goes hand in hand with strangeness and limits.

01:14:29.433 --> 01:14:32.090
Among those limits is its token usage.

01:14:32.090 --> 01:14:48.312
Fable is twice as expensive as Opus, and it burns through tokens at a rate that suggests the answer to how much it costs in production is “a lot,” though its clever delegation to cheaper models may lower the real price considerably.

01:14:48.312 --> 01:14:59.290
The guardrails for Fable also trip at the faintest hint of a security problem, defaulting to the less powerful Claude 4.8 Opus, and it happens way too often.

01:14:59.290 --> 01:15:02.017
And the jagged frontier is still there.

01:15:02.017 --> 01:15:16.142
For example, the AI still writes in the same weird style (in fact the software Fable produces bears traces of Claudisms; so do its progress reports, all that carrying the weight and earning the answer).

01:15:16.142 --> 01:15:23.483
But the deeper strangeness is how little I had to do, and how little I could see while it was being done.

01:15:23.483 --> 01:15:29.707
Last year I called this working with a wizard: you chant the spell and something happens.

01:15:29.707 --> 01:15:35.930
With Fable the spell has gotten powerful enough that I am no longer sure I am the wizard.

01:15:35.930 --> 01:15:37.608
I am closer to a patron.

01:15:37.608 --> 01:15:41.873
I describe what I want, I pay for it, and I judge the result.

01:15:41.873 --> 01:15:48.796
The conjuring happens somewhere I cannot watch, in hundreds of small choices I never get a vote on.

01:15:48.796 --> 01:15:51.942
The work has shifted from process to outcome.

01:15:51.942 --> 01:15:54.180
I no longer steer; I commission.

01:15:54.180 --> 01:16:08.584
It is possible the sidelining is temporary, just an artifact of interfaces that haven’t caught up, and that we’ll get better windows into what these models are doing and better ways to steer them midstream.

01:16:08.584 --> 01:16:20.750
It is also possible that the opposite is true: that the more capable the model, the less there is for a human to meaningfully do, and the black box is the price of the power.

01:16:20.750 --> 01:16:24.596
I suspect that is more likely to be the real direction.

01:16:24.596 --> 01:16:28.442
None of this is a loss of control in the obvious sense.

01:16:28.442 --> 01:16:37.392
I can still steer Fable, and it follows instructions remarkably well: the more ambitious the instruction, the better the result.

01:16:37.392 --> 01:16:40.469
But steering is no longer the same as doing.

01:16:40.469 --> 01:16:49.559
I brief the model, it spins up its own agents to research and write and check one another’s work, and what comes back is finished.

01:16:49.559 --> 01:16:52.146
A patron commissions a single artist.

01:16:52.146 --> 01:17:01.096
Fable is closer to a whole studio, where I am the client who signs off on the final work without ever setting foot on the floor.

01:17:01.096 --> 01:17:02.443
To markets and tech.

01:17:02.443 --> 01:17:08.439
A sharp take from the account Signulll: Meta, he argues, has become narratively homeless.

01:17:08.439 --> 01:17:10.392
meta is narratively homeless.

01:17:10.392 --> 01:17:21.238
they own the largest distribution surface in human history and yet they don't live anywhere that the ppl minting the next decade's mythology actually congregate.

01:17:21.238 --> 01:17:29.456
that's a problem for recruiting the few good ppl they still want, and for everyone betting on where the future gets built.

01:17:29.456 --> 01:17:34.710
you can't be the future from outside the layer that decides what counts as it.

01:17:34.710 --> 01:17:40.908
if i were them, i'd acquire some ppl who understand how to craft a narrative on this medium.

01:17:40.908 --> 01:17:44.007
google briefly did it but now fell flat again.

01:17:44.007 --> 01:17:50.357
The Wall Street Journal reports Apple will raise prices, driven by a memory-chip crunch.

01:17:50.357 --> 01:17:58.224
ET
Tim Cook said price increases on Apple products are “unavoidable” due to surging memory and storage costs.

01:17:58.224 --> 01:18:06.234
Skyrocketing demand from AI companies for memory and storage chips has quadrupled their prices since last year.

01:18:06.234 --> 01:18:15.472
Morgan Stanley estimates memory wafers for consumer tech will fall 15% short of demand by 2027 as suppliers give priority to AI.

01:18:15.472 --> 01:18:19.874
This summary was generated with AI and reviewed by an editor.

01:18:19.874 --> 01:18:24.854
Read more about how we use artificial intelligence in our journalism.

01:18:24.854 --> 01:18:49.824
Tim Cook said price increases on Apple products are “unavoidable” due to surging memory and storage costs.View more
Apple AAPL -1.10%decrease; down pointing triangle plans to raise prices on its products to offset the surging costs of memory and storage chips, Chief Executive Tim Cook said in an exclusive interview with The Wall Street Journal.

01:18:49.824 --> 01:18:54.010
“Unfortunately, price increases are unavoidable,” he said.

01:18:54.010 --> 01:19:16.815
“We’re doing our best to mitigate the huge increases that are being passed to us, and we’ve been trying to shield our customers from the increases, but the situation has become unsustainable.”
Cook declined to offer details on the timing or scale of the planned price increases, nor which products would be affected.

01:19:16.815 --> 01:19:27.207
Apple’s next major product launch is likely to be in September when it releases the iPhone 18 lineup, expected to include a new foldable iPhone.

01:19:27.207 --> 01:19:31.970
Price increases, especially for Macs and iPads, could come sooner.

01:19:31.970 --> 01:19:38.032
Apple raised the starting price of the Mac Mini last month in between launch events.

01:19:38.032 --> 01:19:53.260
Skyrocketing demand for memory and storage chips from artificial-intelligence companies has pushed up their cost so much that Apple would have to raise device prices substantially to maintain its profit margins.

01:19:53.260 --> 01:20:06.033
Passing the higher cost on to consumers while maintaining its profit margin would add about $270 to the price of the next iPhone Pro model, estimates research firm TechInsights.

01:20:06.033 --> 01:20:24.941
[This story explains the math behind a possible price tag of $1,299 for the anticipated iPhone 18 Pro.]
Chips for memory and storage are key components inside most computing devices, including smartphones, laptops, game consoles, medical equipment and even cars.

01:20:24.941 --> 01:20:36.272
But now AI servers are gobbling up rapidly increasing volumes of those chips, so even a company as rich and powerful as Apple is struggling to secure supply.

01:20:36.272 --> 01:20:49.551
Since last year, when Google, Microsoft, Meta and Amazon began announcing big increases in their capital spending budgets, the prices for memory and storage chips have both quadrupled.

01:20:49.551 --> 01:20:54.314
TechInsights expects both prices to continue increasing into 2027.

01:20:54.314 --> 01:21:12.284
Memory, also called DRAM, and storage, also called NAND, are like elements of a mid-20th-century office: The memory is a desk that holds all the papers a worker needs to perform a task, while storage is the filing cabinet that holds everything else.

01:21:12.284 --> 01:21:21.233
Smartphones use DRAM memory to run apps currently in use; they use NAND storage to file away photos and videos, for example.

01:21:21.233 --> 01:21:37.976
Cook said prices for memory and storage are both issues for the company, though he focused on the DRAM market in particular, calling out the increased allocations going to so-called high-bandwidth memory that is used for AI servers.

01:21:37.976 --> 01:21:47.357
“There’s less supply at a time when consumers want devices and the memory guys are passing along huge price increases,” said Cook.

01:21:47.357 --> 01:21:54.502
“We definitely need memory pricing and supply to return to reasonable levels for consumer products.

01:21:54.502 --> 01:22:04.389
That’s the bottom line.”
Three companies dominate the market for DRAM memory: Samsung and SK Hynix in South Korea, and Micron in the U.S.

01:22:04.389 --> 01:22:10.379
Makers of NAND storage include those three companies as well as Kioxia and Sandisk.

01:22:10.379 --> 01:22:23.730
Their stock prices, along with their profits, have exploded over the past twelve months: Micron and SK Hynix shares have risen more than 800% while Kioxia and Sandisk have risen 4,600%.

01:22:23.730 --> 01:22:36.937
Memory companies are building more factories: Morgan Stanley forecasts that production capacity for DRAM wafers, the silicon discs on which chips are patterned, will grow 30% by 2027.

01:22:36.937 --> 01:22:47.185
Yet as suppliers prioritize the specialized AI memory, wafers for consumer tech will fall up to 15% short of demand, Morgan Stanley estimates.

01:22:47.185 --> 01:22:59.020
China has national champion companies in memory and storage, but due to national-security rules, American companies would likely require licenses to work with them.

01:22:59.020 --> 01:23:19.588
When asked if those restrictions should be loosened, Cook said: “I think everything needs to be on the table,” adding, “I think we should look at all supply.”
Companies that make PCs, game consoles, smartphones and more have raised prices, including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and Nintendo.

01:23:19.588 --> 01:23:36.476
A consortium of industry associations recently sent a letter to Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent and Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick complaining about the overallocation of memory to AI buyers and asking for help to increase supply.

01:23:36.476 --> 01:23:42.321
Morgan Stanley estimates a 15% bump for prices of smartphones and PCs in the U.S.

01:23:42.321 --> 01:23:43.043
this year.

01:23:43.043 --> 01:23:51.847
This price hike will have a limited impact on the consumer price index, which has only a small weighting for such devices.

01:23:51.847 --> 01:23:58.054
Yet any price increase on the popular iPhone is likely to grab Washington’s attention.

01:23:58.054 --> 01:24:07.652
Compounding the issue is Apple’s need for additional DRAM to support more AI features, including a rebooted Siri announced last week.

01:24:07.652 --> 01:24:18.477
And the company has long used NAND storage upgrades to boost profits, charging $100 to $200 for extra increments that cost it just a fraction of that.

01:24:18.477 --> 01:24:25.333
In the interview, Cook said Apple stands ready to use its cash reserves to boost memory supply.

01:24:25.333 --> 01:24:31.396
“We’re willing to use our balance sheet to help be a part of the solution,” he said.

01:24:31.396 --> 01:24:36.520
“Obviously, more capacity is needed.”
Cook declined to offer specifics.

01:24:36.520 --> 01:24:45.180
It is unclear how Apple could match, let alone beat, the deal terms that AI hyperscalers are offering to lock up supply.

01:24:45.180 --> 01:24:57.665
Those companies are signing three-to-five year agreements with huge cash prepayments that Apple is unlikely willing to match, given its long history of disciplined spending.

01:24:57.665 --> 01:25:05.315
Cook said Apple wouldn’t use its cash and silicon expertise to build its own memory and storage factories.

01:25:05.315 --> 01:25:07.913
“We can’t do everything,” said Cook.

01:25:07.913 --> 01:25:23.140
“We know what we’re good at.”
Apple spends in the low tens of billions of dollars per year on memory and storage, according to people familiar with its costs, making it one of the largest customers in the world.

01:25:23.140 --> 01:25:33.099
Historically it has used its heft to wring the lowest prices out of suppliers, playing them off each other and leaving them little profit.

01:25:33.099 --> 01:25:38.945
As AI companies have stormed into the market, suddenly Apple has to wait in line.

01:25:38.945 --> 01:25:51.647
Cook said during his time working in the electronics supply chain, from IBM to Compaq to Apple, he had never seen a commodity price swing like the one from the past six months.

01:25:51.647 --> 01:25:54.678
“This is a hundred-year flood,” said Cook.

01:25:54.678 --> 01:26:02.472
“I’ve never seen anything like it in any area in over 40 years.”
