02:01:21.220 --> 02:01:23.204
Two from the history shelf.

02:01:23.204 --> 02:01:27.758
First, a painter born in 1824 to a Jewish family in Groningen.

02:01:27.758 --> 02:01:37.747
Born in 1824 to a Jewish family in Groningen, painter Jozef Israëls rose to become the most celebrated Dutch artist of the 19th century.

02:01:37.747 --> 02:01:42.815
His moving scene “A Jewish Wedding,” in the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam.

02:01:42.815 --> 02:01:46.728
And the day Albert Einstein received a ticker-tape parade.

02:01:46.728 --> 02:01:52.733
Albert Einstein received a historic ticker tape parade in New York City on April 15 1921.

02:01:52.733 --> 02:01:57.524
Making him the only scientist ever to be honored with this celebration.

02:01:57.524 --> 02:02:05.013
It was during his first trip to the United States to promote the creation of the Hebrew University in Jerusalem

02:02:05.013 --> 02:02:06.725
Finally, the long read.

02:02:06.725 --> 02:02:13.274
A new paper tries to measure AI's real impact on productivity across nineteen economies.

02:02:13.274 --> 02:02:14.614
Here is the essay.

02:02:14.614 --> 02:02:57.555
The Machine Already Showed Up in the Numbers
How economists measured AI's productivity contribution from what has already happened, and found roughly $1.26 trillion a year

About: this essay analyzes "Measuring the Impact of AI on Productivity" by Benjamin Verschuere and Angus Cameron of Liminal Capital, a 76-page empirical study that estimates artificial intelligence's contribution to trend productivity growth across the United States and eighteen other economies through the end of 2025, identified from observed sectoral outcomes rather than from forecasts of diffusion.

02:02:57.555 --> 02:03:11.397
For most of the past three years, the question of what artificial intelligence will do to the economy has been answered with forecasts, and the forecasts have not agreed with each other.

02:03:11.397 --> 02:03:28.886
At one end, Daron Acemoglu, applying a classic accounting argument about task-level cost savings, projected that AI would lift total factor productivity in the United States by a cumulative two-thirds of one percent over a full decade.

02:03:28.886 --> 02:03:38.561
At the other end, a team at Goldman Sachs led by Jan Hatzius projected one-and-a-half percent per year, every year, for ten years.

02:03:38.561 --> 02:03:45.556
That is more than an order of magnitude of disagreement, and the disagreement is not a detail.

02:03:45.556 --> 02:04:06.022
It is a sign that nobody actually knew, because every one of these estimates was built the same way: you make structural assumptions about how fast the technology will diffuse and how many tasks it can substitute for, you turn the crank, and a number comes out the other end.

02:04:06.022 --> 02:04:15.176
What none of them did was look at whether the productivity signature they were predicting had already appeared in the data.

02:04:15.176 --> 02:04:20.460
That is the gap the paper I want to walk you through sets out to close.

02:04:20.460 --> 02:04:29.242
Its authors, Benjamin Verschuere and Angus Cameron, take the opposite approach from the entire forecasting literature.

02:04:29.242 --> 02:04:32.591
They do not project forward from assumptions.

02:04:32.591 --> 02:04:42.042
They measure backward from what has already happened in the national accounts since ChatGPT was released in late November 2022.

02:04:42.042 --> 02:04:48.889
The headline result is large and worth stating plainly before we examine how they got there.

02:04:48.889 --> 02:05:08.089
They estimate that at the end-of-2025 run rate, AI is contributing approximately $878 billion per year to trend productivity growth in the United States, with a ninety-five percent confidence interval running from about $602 billion to about $1.155 trillion.

02:05:08.089 --> 02:05:26.695
That single figure raises the aggregate productivity growth rate of the five sectors they study from a counterfactual of plus 2.2 percent per year, which is roughly what the economy would have done without AI, to a realized plus 5.0 percent per year.

02:05:26.695 --> 02:05:44.556
Add in the twelve European economies they pool together, which contribute about $138 billion, and China, which contributes about $240 billion, and the combined figure across these three regions reaches approximately $1.26 trillion per year.

02:05:44.556 --> 02:05:47.309
These are not predictions about 2030.

02:05:47.309 --> 02:06:07.403
They are measurements of a productivity flow that the authors argue is already running through the books, and the entire methodological burden of the paper is to convince you that this flow is real, that it is AI, and that it is not something else wearing an AI costume.

02:06:07.403 --> 02:06:13.506
To follow the argument you need one concept, and it is the keystone of everything.

02:06:13.506 --> 02:06:23.701
The authors measure how exposed each sector of the economy is to AI using a construct they call Workflow Completeness, written as C-star.

02:06:23.701 --> 02:06:28.464
The idea is mechanical and, once you see it, hard to argue with.

02:06:28.464 --> 02:07:01.954
They take the roughly 18,796 individual task statements catalogued in the Department of Labor's O*NET database, the exhaustive inventory of what people actually do in their jobs, and they score each one on a four-point scale according to how completely AI can perform it on its own, from zero, meaning AI cannot do it, through partial assistance and substantial completion with human oversight, up to three, meaning end-to-end autonomous performance.

02:07:01.954 --> 02:07:15.424
They roll those task scores up to occupations, weighting by importance, and then roll occupations up to sectors, weighting by how many people each sector employs in each occupation.

02:07:15.424 --> 02:07:24.727
The result is a single number for each sector that captures the ceiling of what AI can structurally do to that sector's work.

02:07:24.727 --> 02:07:30.978
Information and Professional Services score high, around 0.79 and 0.66 respectively.

02:07:30.978 --> 02:07:33.955
Construction scores 0.18, Industry 0.14.

02:07:33.955 --> 02:08:02.235
The crucial validation, established in a companion paper, is that this theoretical measure tracks what firms actually report doing: across nine sectors, C-star correlates with firm-reported AI adoption from the Census Bureau's Business Trends and Outlook Survey at 0.89, and it converges with an entirely independent AI-exposure measure built by Felten, Raj, and Seamans at 0.937.

02:08:02.235 --> 02:08:06.551
So C-star is not just a guess about where AI could matter.

02:08:06.551 --> 02:08:11.314
It is a validated proxy for where AI is actually being deployed.

02:08:11.314 --> 02:08:13.249
Now the logic of the test.

02:08:13.249 --> 02:08:37.808
If AI is genuinely driving post-ChatGPT productivity, then two things should be visible simultaneously in the data: productivity in high-C-star sectors should grow faster than in low-C-star sectors after the fourth quarter of 2022, and the gap should widen with time as adoption diffuses, rather than appearing as a one-time jump.

02:08:37.808 --> 02:08:44.432
The authors build a panel difference-in-differences specification to detect exactly this.

02:08:44.432 --> 02:08:57.009
They strip out, for each sector, its own pre-2019 linear productivity trend, so they are working with the excess productivity above where each sector "should" have been.

02:08:57.009 --> 02:09:11.075
Then they let the data answer a single question: after ChatGPT, does the productivity gap between high- and low-exposure sectors widen quarter by quarter, at a rate that scales with C-star?

02:09:11.075 --> 02:09:21.270
The coefficient that answers this, which they call delta-beta, comes back at plus 2.088 percentage points per quarter per unit of C-star.

02:09:21.270 --> 02:09:45.234
To translate that into something concrete: evaluated across the spread from Construction to Information, it implies that Information's productivity grows about 1.27 percentage points per quarter faster than Construction's, purely from the AI-scaled component, over and above any common shock that hit every sector at once.

02:09:45.234 --> 02:09:57.588
That common shock, by the way, is deliberately absorbed into time fixed effects, which is what makes this specification more conservative than a simple cross-section.

02:09:57.588 --> 02:10:05.849
The pandemic-era productivity surge, whatever caused it, gets netted out rather than mistakenly credited to AI.

02:10:05.849 --> 02:10:19.691
The authors are unusually careful, almost obsessive, about inference, and here is where a sophisticated reader should pay attention rather than glaze over, because the care is the point.

02:10:19.691 --> 02:10:39.040
With only nine sector clusters, standard asymptotic statistics are unreliable, so they run what they call an inference cascade, four analytic methods plus two resampling methods, and they report all of them, including the ones that look worst for their result.

02:10:39.040 --> 02:10:46.408
Plain OLS, which ignores the panel structure, gives a p-value of 0.090, just short of significance.

02:10:46.408 --> 02:10:59.506
Every cluster-robust analytic method, by contrast, clears conventional thresholds comfortably: sector-clustered and time-clustered both below 0.001, two-way clustered at 0.005.

02:10:59.506 --> 02:11:08.065
Their designated primary test, a wild cluster bootstrap with Rademacher weights and sector clustering, gives 0.016.

02:11:08.065 --> 02:11:24.288
The most demanding test of all, a permutation test that shuffles the C-star labels across sectors ten thousand times and asks how often random reassignment produces a t-statistic as large as the real one, gives 0.0056.

02:11:24.288 --> 02:11:27.935
The observed statistic ranked 56th out of 10,001.

02:11:27.935 --> 02:11:42.075
The honest weak spot, which they flag rather than hide, is that the single most conservative bootstrap variant, Mammen weights on sector clusters, sits at 0.111, above the five percent line.

02:11:42.075 --> 02:11:57.108
Their summary of their own result is exactly right: it holds under the primary inference cascade, falls short of significance only under that one most conservative variant, and survives everything else.

02:11:57.108 --> 02:12:09.313
But statistical significance of a slope is not the same as proof that AI caused it, and the authors know that correlation consistent with causation is a weak claim.

02:12:09.313 --> 02:12:17.053
Their real identification rests on something more demanding, which they call the joint-pattern argument.

02:12:17.053 --> 02:12:53.371
AI-driven labor substitution should leave a specific four-part fingerprint: output rising with C-star, employment falling with C-star, the pattern emerging precisely at the fourth quarter of 2022 and not at some arbitrary earlier or later date, and a cross-sectional signature mechanically distinct from the pandemic-era dynamics that the literature attributes to compositional reallocation, labor-quality cleansing, and capital deepening, none of which scale with task-level AI exposure.

02:12:53.371 --> 02:13:02.227
And this is where the paper becomes genuinely convincing, because the fingerprint reverses sign across the two regimes.

02:13:02.227 --> 02:13:20.683
During the pandemic window, productivity gains were not ranked by AI exposure at all; the correlation between productivity change and C-star was actually negative, minus 0.46, and high-exposure sectors were adding employment, correlation plus 0.79.

02:13:20.683 --> 02:13:26.488
Information, the highest-exposure sector, was the weakest productivity gainer.

02:13:26.488 --> 02:13:37.949
The pandemic gains concentrated in Industry, Trade, and Education, exactly the sectors where excess-layoff dynamics and labor-quality cleansing dominated.

02:13:37.949 --> 02:13:48.070
After ChatGPT, both correlations flip: productivity change now correlates with C-star at plus 0.86, and employment change at minus 0.60.

02:13:48.070 --> 02:13:59.978
Information goes from laggard to leader, gaining 37.3 percent in productivity through 26.3 percent value-added growth combined with an 8 percent employment cut.

02:13:59.978 --> 02:14:06.080
This is the output-up, labor-down signature, and it is sharply scaled by exposure.

02:14:06.080 --> 02:14:26.323
It is also consistent with independent labor-market evidence: Gad Levanon's documentation of roughly three million missing jobs concentrated in high-AI-exposure white-collar sectors since late 2022, arising from output continuing to grow while headcount stagnated or fell.

02:14:26.323 --> 02:14:37.709
The authors then do something most empirical papers skip: they line up the leading alternative explanations and shoot them down one by one, ten in total.

02:14:37.709 --> 02:14:51.998
The most serious is that high-C-star sectors simply invested heavily in IT during the 2020-2021 remote-work pivot, and the post-2022 productivity is the delayed payoff of that capital, not AI.

02:14:51.998 --> 02:14:57.059
So they run a horse race, adding IT intensity as a parallel control.

02:14:57.059 --> 02:15:07.626
The AI-scaled coefficient barely moves, from 2.088 to 2.051, while the IT coefficient comes back at 0.013, essentially zero and insignificant.

02:15:07.626 --> 02:15:18.715
The next candidate is the over-hiring correction: the tech layoffs of 2022-2024 mechanically raised value added per worker as the denominator shrank.

02:15:18.715 --> 02:15:30.102
This is the closest competitor, and the authors handle it with a cross-sectional inversion test that is, to my mind, the cleverest argument in the paper.

02:15:30.102 --> 02:15:40.074
Under the over-hiring story, the sector with the biggest hiring surplus should produce the biggest subsequent productivity correction.

02:15:40.074 --> 02:15:51.609
Transport and Logistics had the largest hiring surplus in the entire dataset, plus 15.7 percent above its pre-pandemic peak, more than twice Information's.

02:15:51.609 --> 02:16:02.996
Yet Transport added jobs after ChatGPT and produced excess productivity of only 3.2 percentage points, while Information cut headcount and produced 10.9.

02:16:02.996 --> 02:16:07.684
The pattern is exactly backward from what over-hiring predicts.

02:16:07.684 --> 02:16:16.540
When controlled for directly, over-hiring reduces the estimated AI effect by about a quarter but leaves it significant.

02:16:16.540 --> 02:16:39.164
Then comes cost of capital, the monetary-tightening story, and it fails on timing in a way that is almost too neat: between the policy-rate peak in late 2023 and the end of 2025, the federal funds rate fell by 1.4 percentage points while the C-star productivity gradient rose from plus 8.6 to plus 14.35.

02:16:39.164 --> 02:16:47.127
The gradient accelerated through the easing cycle, the opposite of what a cost-of-capital channel predicts.

02:16:47.127 --> 02:17:01.416
Cognitive task content, measurement artifact, date placebos, mean reversion, jobless-recovery dynamics, and a 2008-recovery placebo round out the list, and none reproduces the joint signature.

02:17:01.416 --> 02:17:16.673
The date placebos are particularly reassuring: when you assign a fake treatment date of 2018 or 2020, the estimated effect comes back negative, minus 1.52 and minus 0.78, signed against the real direction.

02:17:16.673 --> 02:17:21.882
The specification does not generically detect any post-period feature.

02:17:21.882 --> 02:17:25.380
It detects a post-ChatGPT feature specifically.

02:17:25.380 --> 02:17:31.036
The cross-country extension is where the story gains both reach and texture.

02:17:31.036 --> 02:17:39.892
Applying the same machinery to eighteen other economies, the authors find effects that scale with deployment intensity.

02:17:39.892 --> 02:17:59.539
The twelve European economies, pooled, show AI contributing plus 0.614 percentage points per quarter, equivalent to plus 2.46 per year, about 31 percent of the US rate, statistically significant under analytic two-way clustering but borderline under the bootstrap.

02:17:59.539 --> 02:18:15.391
China, dated to its own 2023 treatment because ChatGPT was blocked and domestic large language models reached enterprise scale only in mid-to-late 2023, shows plus 3.80 per year, roughly 48 percent of the US rate.

02:18:15.391 --> 02:18:23.726
The US and China are the two largest single-country effects, in the same order of magnitude, with the US larger.

02:18:23.726 --> 02:18:37.048
Germany and Sweden are individually significant; Finland is marginal; the rest of the major economies return positive but insignificant estimates that the authors do not oversell.

02:18:37.048 --> 02:18:53.048
And here is the most striking cross-country finding, the one that reframes what AI is doing: in six of the twelve EU economies, plus Japan and Australia, the counterfactual productivity trend without AI is negative.

02:18:53.048 --> 02:18:56.695
AI is not accelerating growth in these economies.

02:18:56.695 --> 02:19:01.681
It is the difference between stagnation and modest positive growth.

02:19:01.681 --> 02:19:10.239
The EU-pooled decomposition makes this concrete: without AI, minus 0.3 percent per year; with AI, plus 0.5 percent.

02:19:10.239 --> 02:19:22.221
The authors put it sharply, that in much of advanced Europe and East Asia, AI is the difference between trend productivity stagnation and modest positive growth.

02:19:22.221 --> 02:19:27.728
The three policy implications follow directly and are worth carrying away.

02:19:27.728 --> 02:19:41.645
First, monetary: an AI-driven productivity acceleration is a positive supply shock, raising potential output without raising demand, which calls for accommodation rather than restriction.

02:19:41.645 --> 02:20:06.874
The US contribution at roughly 3.0 percent of nominal GDP per year is an order of magnitude larger than the supply shocks that have featured in Federal Reserve deliberations over the past decade, which means output-gap and Phillips-curve frameworks that ignore it will systematically understate slack and bias policy toward overtightening.

02:20:06.874 --> 02:20:33.889
Second, fiscal: productivity-driven nominal GDP growth raises the growth rate in the debt-sustainability identity without raising the interest rate, widening the gap that determines fiscal headroom, and it does so without the inflation tax or the contractionary cost of the alternatives, a genuinely Pareto-superior channel that accrues most to the United States.

02:20:33.889 --> 02:20:46.168
Third, labor: the policy world's one-size-fits-all "AI displacement" narrative is poorly suited to what the data show, because three distinct patterns are operating.

02:20:46.168 --> 02:20:52.420
The US shows substitution, output up and labor down, calling for transition support.

02:20:52.420 --> 02:21:06.932
Europe shows buffering, high-exposure sectors holding flat while low-exposure ones decline, calling for attention to the structural impediments preventing AI from translating into measured gains.

02:21:06.932 --> 02:21:23.081
China shows augmentation, where Information productivity grew about 94 percent over 2019-2025 alongside roughly 9 percent employment growth, AI raising the productivity of existing workers rather than displacing them.

02:21:23.081 --> 02:21:32.086
There is a final, quieter contribution that deserves mention because it indicts the tools policymakers currently rely on.

02:21:32.086 --> 02:21:48.533
The authors test whether published digital-readiness composites, the WIPO Global Innovation Index and an OECD digital-economy composite, predict which economies actually translate AI capability into measured productivity.

02:21:48.533 --> 02:21:49.426
They do not.

02:21:49.426 --> 02:22:06.171
Across the seventeen OECD economies with both metrics, the correlations are 0.055 and 0.081, statistically indistinguishable from zero, with confidence intervals spanning from substantially negative to substantially positive.

02:22:06.171 --> 02:22:17.781
Korea and the United Kingdom rank high on readiness but show small or negative productivity gradients; Italy and Portugal rank lower but show positive ones.

02:22:17.781 --> 02:22:25.372
Infrastructure-and-skills readiness, it turns out, does not capture what drives differential outcomes.

02:22:25.372 --> 02:22:58.787
The durable contribution of this paper, the authors argue, is not the specific dollar figures, which will shift as new data arrive, but the measurement framework itself: a portable, sector-level, outcome-anchored way to monitor AI's productivity contribution quarter by quarter, requiring no proprietary survey infrastructure, that surfaces precisely the gaps between what AI can do and what it is actually delivering in each sector of each economy.

02:22:58.787 --> 02:23:11.513
They even stake out six falsifiers, patterns in 2026-2027 data that would prove them wrong, which is the mark of researchers who believe they have measured something real.

02:23:11.513 --> 02:23:20.295
The AI productivity question, they conclude, is no longer one that requires waiting on future data to begin answering.

02:23:20.295 --> 02:23:40.909
The acceleration is already visible in standard national-accounts data, measurable under conventional inference, and asymmetric across the major economies in ways that have direct and immediate implications for how monetary, fiscal, and labor-market policy should be conducted.

02:23:40.909 --> 02:23:42.249
That's the digest.

02:23:42.249 --> 02:23:50.956
Every word came from something you bookmarked today; links to each source are in the show notes and on every chapter.

02:23:50.956 --> 02:23:52.296
Made just for you.

02:23:52.296 --> 02:23:53.040
Talk soon.
